
[1]diminutive

   DIMINUTIVE, a. Small; little; narrow; contracted; as a diminutive race
   of men or other animals; a diminutive thought.

   DIMINUTIVE, n. In grammar, a word formed from another word, usually an
   appellative or generic term, to express a little thing of the kind; as,
   in Latin, lapillus, a little stone, from lapis; cellula, a little cell,
   from cella, a cell; in French, maisonnette, a little house, from
   maison, a house; in English, manikin, a little man, from man.
